        // ── Overview (Article) ───────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Vendors Overview",
            Slug = "vendors-overview",
            Summary = "What vendors are, how to manage them, payment terms, and how vendors connect to purchase orders and inventory.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/vendors"]""",
            Tags = """["vendors","procurement"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Vendors Overview\n\nVendors is your supplier directory — the one place a buyer keeps every company you purchase from. Raw-material mills, tooling shops, distributors, service providers, subcontractors: each one gets a record with its contacts, address, payment terms, and full ordering history. When you're deciding who to buy from, this is where you look.\n\n### What you keep on a vendor\n\nA vendor is any outside company you buy goods or services from. For each one you track:\n- **Company name** — the supplier's legal or trade name, the way it reads on your purchase orders\n- **Contact** — the person you deal with, plus their email and phone\n- **Address** — where the vendor ships and bills from\n- **Payment terms** — what you negotiated: Net 30, Net 60, Due on Receipt, and so on\n- **Active or inactive** — whether you're still buying from them\n\n### How vendors tie into the rest of your buying\n\n**Purchase orders:** Every PO goes to a vendor. When you raise one, you pick the vendor and the order starts from their address and payment terms, so you're not re-keying them. Open a vendor and you see every order you've ever placed with them.\n\n**Receiving and traceability:** When a shipment lands, receiving ties it back to the PO and the vendor. That gives you a clean trail — who supplied what, when it arrived, and whether it passed inspection — which is exactly what you reach for during a quality escape or an audit.\n\n**Performance scorecard:** Each vendor carries a scorecard that grades how they actually perform: on-time delivery, quality acceptance, quantity accuracy, and total spend. It rolls up to a score out of 100 and an A-through-F letter grade, weighted toward what matters most to a buyer — delivery (40%), quality (30%), price (20%), quantity (10%). Use it in sourcing reviews and QBRs to reward good suppliers and put weak ones on notice.\n\n**When accounting runs the vendor list:** If your shop keeps its books in an outside accounting system (like QuickBooks), that system owns the vendor list — so vendors here become view-only and you make edits over there instead. When there's no accounting system connected, you manage vendors here directly: add, edit, and retire them yourself.\n\n### When you'll come here\n\n- Onboarding a new supplier before you cut your first PO to them\n- Updating a contact or renegotiated payment terms\n- Reviewing a supplier's delivery and quality record on the scorecard\n- Retiring a supplier you no longer use (their history stays intact)\n- Pulling up order history to see everything you've bought from one supplier","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Walkthrough ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
