            AppRoutes = """["/vendors"]""",
            Tags = """["vendors","quiz","procurement"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"passingScore":80,"questionsPerQuiz":8,"shuffleOptions":true,"showExplanationsAfterSubmit":true,"questions":[{"id":"vn1","text":"You need to onboard a new raw material supplier before placing your first purchase order. What is the correct first step?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Go to Purchase Orders and create a PO — the vendor will be auto-created"},{"id":"b","text":"Navigate to Vendors, click New Vendor, then pick a setup path (Quick add or Guided setup) and fill in at least the company name","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Add the supplier to Inventory as a new storage location"},{"id":"d","text":"Go to Admin → Reference Data and add the vendor as a lookup value"}],"explanation":"New suppliers must be created in the Vendors module first. Click New Vendor in the page header — you then choose Quick add (needs only the company name to start) or Guided setup (a step-by-step wizard for strategic or approved vendors). Either way, the only required field is Company Name; the vendor then becomes available in PO vendor dropdowns."},{"id":"vn2","text":"Which field is the only required field when creating a new vendor?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Contact Name"},{"id":"b","text":"Email"},{"id":"c","text":"Company Name","isCorrect":true},{"id":"d","text":"Payment Terms"}],"explanation":"Company Name is the only required field on the vendor form. All other fields — contact name, email, phone, address, payment terms, and notes — are optional."},{"id":"vn3","text":"A vendor's scorecard shows a grade of 'C' with an overall score of 68/100. What does this tell you?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The vendor has been deactivated due to poor performance"},{"id":"b","text":"The vendor is performing below average based on weighted criteria: delivery (40%), quality (30%), price (20%), and quantity accuracy (10%)","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The vendor has only completed a few POs and doesn't have enough data for a full evaluation"},{"id":"d","text":"The vendor's payment terms need to be renegotiated"}],"explanation":"The vendor scorecard grades performance on a 100-point scale using four weighted criteria: On-Time Delivery (40%), Quality Acceptance (30%), Price (20%), and Quantity Accuracy (10%). A 'C' grade with 68/100 indicates below-average performance across these areas."},{"id":"vn4","text":"You want to see all purchase orders placed with a specific vendor. Where do you find this?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Go to Purchase Orders and filter by vendor name"},{"id":"b","text":"Click the vendor row to open the detail dialog, then select the Purchase Orders tab","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Run a report in the Reports module filtered by vendor"},{"id":"d","text":"Check the vendor's Notes field for PO references"}],"explanation":"The vendor detail dialog has three tabs: Info, Purchase Orders, and Scorecard. The Purchase Orders tab shows a data table with all POs linked to that vendor, including PO number, status, expected delivery date, and creation date."},{"id":"vn5","text":"Your company just connected QuickBooks Online as the accounting provider. What happens to vendor management here?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Nothing changes — vendors are managed independently in both systems"},{"id":"b","text":"Vendor management becomes read-only here — vendor records sync from QuickBooks, and edits must be made in the accounting system","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"All vendor records are deleted and replaced with QuickBooks data"},{"id":"d","text":"Vendors can only be created here and pushed to QuickBooks"}],"explanation":"When an accounting provider is connected, vendor management becomes read-only here. Vendor records sync from QuickBooks automatically. The vendor list, PO history, and scorecard remain fully functional — only direct editing is disabled."},{"id":"vn6","text":"You no longer do business with a supplier but want to preserve their purchase history. What should you do?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Delete the vendor — PO history is retained separately"},{"id":"b","text":"Open the vendor detail, click the Deactivate button on the Info tab to set them as Inactive","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Remove all POs associated with the vendor, then delete the vendor record"},{"id":"d","text":"Change the vendor's payment terms to 'Suspended'"}],"explanation":"Deactivating a vendor preserves the full record including all PO history, scorecard data, and contact information. The vendor simply won't appear in active vendor lists or PO vendor dropdowns. You can reactivate them later if needed."},{"id":"vn7","text":"What payment terms options are available when creating a vendor?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Only Net 30 and Net 60"},{"id":"b","text":"Due on Receipt, Net 15, Net 30, Net 45, Net 60, and COD","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Payment terms are free-text and can be anything"},{"id":"d","text":"Payment terms are set globally in Admin and cannot vary per vendor"}],"explanation":"The Payment Terms dropdown offers standard commercial terms: Due on Receipt, Net 15, Net 30, Net 45, Net 60, and COD (plus a blank 'none' option). These terms are inherited by new POs placed with the vendor."},{"id":"vn8","text":"How does the vendor search box apply your search term?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"It filters automatically a moment after you stop typing; pressing Enter applies it immediately","isCorrect":true},{"id":"b","text":"Search only works on the Company Name field — other fields are ignored"},{"id":"c","text":"You must select a status filter before the search will run"},{"id":"d","text":"Nothing happens until you have typed at least 3 characters"}],"explanation":"The vendor search filters automatically a moment after you stop typing; pressing Enter applies it immediately. It searches across company name, contact name, email, and phone fields. The status filter (All, Active, Inactive) works independently and does not need to be set before searching."},{"id":"vn9","text":"On a vendor's details you see an 'Accounting reference'. What is it telling you?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"A vendor number you type in yourself for internal tracking"},{"id":"b","text":"The vendor's tax identification number (EIN)"},{"id":"c","text":"This vendor came in from your accounting system, and the reference ties it to the same supplier in the books","isCorrect":true},{"id":"d","text":"The account number the vendor has assigned to you as their customer"}],"explanation":"The Accounting reference appears only on vendors that come from your accounting system (such as QuickBooks). It links the supplier here to the same one in the books, so purchasing and AP are looking at one vendor rather than two. You don't type it in — it comes across with the vendor, and it's a signal to make edits over in the accounting system."},{"id":"vn10","text":"Which factor carries the most weight in the vendor scorecard calculation?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Quality Acceptance (30%)"},{"id":"b","text":"Price Competitiveness (20%)"},{"id":"c","text":"On-Time Delivery (40%)","isCorrect":true},{"id":"d","text":"Quantity Accuracy (10%)"}],"explanation":"The vendor scorecard uses four weighted criteria: On-Time Delivery carries the most weight at 40%, followed by Quality Acceptance at 30%, Price at 20%, and Quantity Accuracy at 10%. This reflects that reliable delivery is the most critical factor in vendor performance."}]}"""
        });

        // ── Creating a Vendor: Quick vs Guided (Article) ─────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Creating a Vendor: Quick vs Guided",
            Slug = "vendors-create-quick-vs-guided",
            Summary = "The New Vendor setup choice: when to use Quick add versus the 5-step Guided setup wizard, and what each path captures.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 5,
            AppRoutes = """["/vendors","/vendors/new"]""",
            Tags = """["vendors","procurement","onboarding"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Creating a Vendor: Quick vs Guided\n\nClicking **+ New Vendor** on the Vendors page no longer drops you straight into a form — it opens a small **window** that asks *how* you want to set up the vendor. There are two paths, and choosing the right one saves rework later.\n\n### The choice window\n\nThe window shows two cards:\n\n- **Quick add** (badged *Fast*) — \"Just the essentials — company name and basic contact. Flesh out the rest later.\" This is the dominant, everyday path.\n- **Guided setup** — \"Step-by-step for strategic or approved vendors — classification, address, terms, and the parts they supply.\"\n\nClick a card to choose; the **Cancel** button at the bottom backs out without creating anything.\n\n### Quick add — the everyday path\n\nQuick add opens the flat vendor dialog. The only required field is **Company Name**; contact name, email, phone, address, payment terms, and notes are all optional and can be filled in later. Use Quick add when:\n\n- You just need the vendor to exist so you can put it on a purchase order.\n- It is a one-off or low-volume transactional supplier.\n- You will enrich the record later (or let an accounting sync fill in the details).\n\nThe vendor is created immediately and becomes available in PO vendor dropdowns. You can always open the vendor later and add an address, terms, or catalog parts.\n\n### Guided setup — for strategic / approved vendors\n\nChoosing **Guided setup** opens a step-by-step wizard (the same style used for Parts). It's worth the extra effort for strategic suppliers, approved vendors, or any vendor whose address, terms, and supplied parts you want captured up front. The wizard walks five steps:\n\n1. **Identity** *(required)* — Company name, contact name, email, and phone. This step is what actually creates the vendor, so company name is required here. Until you finish it, nothing is saved.\n2. **Address** *(optional)* — Street, city, state, ZIP, and country for the vendor's billing and shipping address.\n3. **Terms** *(optional)* — Payment terms (Net 30, and so on) and related billing settings.\n4. **Supply Items** *(optional)* — A reminder step. You add the parts this vendor supplies — along with their approval, preferred, and pricing settings — on the vendor's **Catalog** tab after the vendor exists, rather than entering them all here.\n5. **Review** *(required)* — A final summary; confirm to finish.\n\n### Express vs Guided mode inside the wizard\n\nThe wizard has two modes you can switch between. *Guided* mode shows one step at a time with the reasoning available in a side panel; *Express* mode puts the optional steps on a single screen for people who already know what they're entering. Both modes cover the same steps and the same required stops (Identity and Review).\n\n### Save and come back later\n\nThe wizard remembers where you are. Once the Identity step has created the vendor, you can bookmark or share the page and pick up a half-finished setup right where you left off.\n\n### Which should I pick?\n\n| Situation | Path |\n|---|---|\n| Need the vendor on a PO right now | Quick add |\n| One-off or low-volume supplier | Quick add |\n| Strategic / sole-source / AVL partner | Guided setup |\n| You want address + terms + supplied parts captured up front | Guided setup |\n| Importing many vendor-supplied parts | Guided setup, then bulk CSV import on the Catalog tab |\n\nThere is no \"convert from lead\" path for vendors (leads become customers, not suppliers), so the choice is two-way rather than three-way.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Vendor Catalog & AVL (Article) ───────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Vendor Catalog & Approved Vendor List (AVL)",
            Slug = "vendors-catalog-avl",
            Summary = "The Catalog tab on a vendor: the parts a vendor supplies, the Approved (AVL) and Preferred Source flags, bulk CSV import, and how it ties into purchasing.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 6,
            AppRoutes = """["/vendors"]""",
            Tags = """["vendors","catalog","avl","procurement","vendor-parts"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Vendor Catalog & Approved Vendor List (AVL)\n\nEvery vendor has a **Catalog** tab — the list of parts that supplier sells you. For a buyer, this is your sourcing memory: what each vendor can supply, their part number for it, how long it takes, how little you can order, what it costs, and whether they're cleared to supply it at all. It's the same picture you get on a part's **Sources** tab (where you compare vendors for one part), just turned around to answer \"what does *this vendor* sell us?\"\n\n### Opening the Catalog tab\n\nFrom the Vendors list, click a vendor to open it, then click the **Catalog** tab (next to Info, Purchase Orders, and Scorecard). It loads the parts this vendor supplies.\n\n### What each catalog row tells you\n\nEach row is one part this vendor can supply, with the details that are specific to buying it *from them*:\n\n- **Part** — the part number and name from your own parts list.\n- **Vendor Part Number** — the vendor's own catalog number for it. You quote this back to them so you both know exactly what's being ordered.\n- **Vendor MPN** — the manufacturer part number (MPN), used when the vendor is a distributor reselling someone else's part. It can differ from your own drawing's part number, so recording both avoids ordering the wrong thing.\n- **Lead Time (days)**, **Min Order Qty (MOQ)**, **Pack Size** — how long this vendor takes, the least they'll sell you, and how it's packaged. MOQ is the smallest quantity they'll accept on an order.\n- **Country of Origin** and **HTS Code** — where it's made and its customs classification (the HTS code, or Harmonized Tariff Schedule number, drives import duty). You'll want these for trade-compliance and customs paperwork.\n- **Price tiers** — the quantity-break pricing (covered in the *Managing Vendor Pricing* module).\n- **Approved** and **Preferred** flags — see below.\n- **Notes** and **Last Quoted Date** — so you can tell at a glance whether a price is fresh or stale before you rely on it.\n\n### The Approved flag (AVL)\n\nThe **Approved** switch is your **Approved Vendor List (AVL)** marker — the list of suppliers cleared to supply a given part. An approved row means this vendor has passed whatever qualification your shop requires (first-article, certs, quality sign-off) and is fair game to order from. Approved rows show a green check; un-approved ones show a blocked icon. It's how you keep buyers ordering from qualified sources and not from whoever happens to be cheapest that week.\n\n### The Preferred Source flag\n\nThe **Preferred** switch marks your *go-to* supplier for a part — a filled star you can toggle right from the list. A part can have only **one preferred source at a time**: star a new vendor and the star clears on whoever held it before, so \"who do we normally buy this from?\" always has one clean answer. Reordering and any auto-generated POs lean on the preferred vendor's lead time, minimum order quantity, and pack size, so keep it pointed at the supplier you actually want the system to default to.\n\n### Adding, editing, and removing catalog entries\n\n- **+ Add** opens the form to record a part this vendor supplies. The vendor is already set (you're inside it), so you pick the **Part** and fill in the buying details, including the Approved and Preferred toggles.\n- The **edit** (pencil) action reopens the same form to change any field.\n- The **delete** (trash) action drops the part from *this vendor's* catalog. It only says \"this vendor no longer supplies this part\" — your part itself stays put.\n- The **Is Manufacturer** switch says whether the vendor *makes* the part (they're the manufacturer, so you enter one part number) or *distributes* someone else's part (so you record both the vendor's number and the original manufacturer's part number). Getting this right keeps made-here and resold parts from blurring together.\n\n### Bulk import\n\nTo load a distributor's whole catalog or a long price list at once, use **Import** at the top of the Catalog tab. Two steps:\n\n1. **Pick a file** — drag in or browse for a spreadsheet. A **Download template** link gives you the exact columns.\n2. **Preview** — every row comes back marked **Add**, **Update**, or **Error**, with a running count. Rows with a problem show what's wrong, and **Apply** stays grayed out until you fix them and re-import.\n\nApply saves all the adds and updates in one go. It matches on part number, so parts the vendor already lists get updated rather than duplicated.\n\n### How the catalog pays off when you buy\n\nOnce the catalog is filled in, the rest of your buying leans on it:\n\n- **Reordering and auto-generated POs** use your preferred source's lead time, minimum order quantity, and pricing to suggest what and when to buy.\n- **Purchase orders** fill in the vendor's part number and price for you when you add a part they supply — less re-keying, fewer mistakes.\n- The **Approved flag** keeps orders flowing to qualified sources.\n\nBecause the catalog is shared between the supplier and the part, any change shows up in the activity history on **both** the vendor and the part — so whether you're reviewing a supplier or a part, you can see who changed a price, a lead time, or a preference, and when.","sections":[]}"""
        });

