        // ── Managing Vendor Pricing — Price Tiers (Article) ──────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Managing Vendor Pricing — Price Tiers",
            Slug = "vendors-price-tiers",
            Summary = "Quantity-break price tiers on a catalog part: how tiers are picked, currency, effective dating, viewing tier history, and how the right price lands on a PO.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 8,
            AppRoutes = """["/vendors"]""",
            Tags = """["vendors","pricing","price-tiers","procurement","vendor-parts"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Managing Vendor Pricing — Price Tiers\n\nSuppliers rarely quote one flat price — they quote **quantity breaks**: cheaper per unit the more you buy. You capture that on each catalog part as **price tiers**. A tier is one line of a supplier's quote: \"at this quantity (and from this date), the unit price is X in this currency.\" Keep them current and the system prices your POs the way the vendor actually quoted, without you doing the mental math each time.\n\n### Opening the price tiers\n\nOn a vendor's **Catalog** tab, the **Price Tiers** column shows the lowest current price with a small badge counting how many tiers there are. Click the price to open the **Price Tiers** window for that part. It lists the tiers you've entered and has an **Add Tier** form at the bottom.\n\n### What goes in a tier\n\n- **Min Quantity** *(required)* — the smallest order quantity this price applies to. The highest break you clear wins (see the example).\n- **Unit Price** *(required)* — the per-unit price at that break.\n- **Currency** *(required)* — what currency the price is in. You can quote different tiers in different currencies for an overseas supplier, and the price converts when it lands on a PO.\n- **Effective From / Effective To** *(optional)* — the dates the price is good for. Leave Effective To blank for \"current, no end date.\" This is how you load a price increase ahead of time without losing the old price.\n- **Purchase unit** — if you buy the part in more than one unit (each, box, reel), you can tie the tier to one, and a preview shows what that works out to per each.\n- **Notes** *(optional)* — the quote number or a note about the deal.\n\n### How the price gets picked\n\nWhen a price is needed for a quantity, the system takes the tier with the highest Min Quantity you still clear, from the tiers in effect on the order date. That's the unit price that lands on the PO line. Order below the lowest tier and that lowest price is used as the floor — and you'll get a heads-up if you're ordering under the minimum or off the quoted breaks, so a mispriced line doesn't slip through.\n\n### Quantity-break example\n\n| Min Qty | Unit Price |\n|---|---|\n| 1 | $2.00 |\n| 100 | $1.60 |\n| 500 | $1.35 |\n\n- Order 50 → $2.00 each (only the qty-1 break is cleared).\n- Order 250 → $1.60 each (you've cleared 100 but not 500).\n- Order 1,000 → $1.35 each (you've cleared the 500 break).\n\n### Dating prices and keeping the history\n\nYou add a new tier rather than editing an old one in place. Instead of painting over last year's price, you add the new one (often with a future start date), and the old price stays on the record. To look back, use the **history** action on a catalog row to open the **Price Tier History** — the running log of prices added and retired over time. That history is what lets the scorecard measure how much a vendor's prices have crept, and what you hand an auditor when they ask when a price changed.\n\n### Adding and removing tiers\n\n- Fill the **Add Tier** form (Min Quantity, Unit Price, Currency, plus optional dates and notes) and click **Add Tier**. That's the button that saves the tier — **Close** just backs out and won't save a half-filled row.\n- Remove a tier with its **delete** action. Since history is kept, removing a tier records that it was retired rather than pretending it never existed — so you can still see what you were paying back then.\n\n### Where the pricing pays off\n\n- The Catalog/Sources list shows the **lowest current price** as the headline, so you can compare suppliers at a glance.\n- **Purchase order** lines fill in the right break price for the quantity you're ordering, automatically.\n- **Reordering and auto-POs** use your preferred source's pricing when they work out what to buy.\n- The **scorecard's price factor (20%)** compares what you actually paid against the quoted breaks, so a vendor quietly charging over quote shows up.","sections":[]}"""
        });

