            Tags = """["vendors","quiz","catalog","avl","pricing","procurement"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"passingScore":80,"questionsPerQuiz":7,"shuffleOptions":true,"showExplanationsAfterSubmit":true,"questions":[{"id":"vc1","text":"You click + New Vendor to add a strategic, sole-source supplier and want to capture its address, payment terms, and the parts it supplies up front. Which path should you choose?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Quick add — it captures everything in one flat form"},{"id":"b","text":"Guided setup — the 5-step wizard for strategic or approved vendors","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Convert from Lead — promote the supplier lead to a vendor"},{"id":"d","text":"There is no choice; New Vendor always opens the same form"}],"explanation":"New Vendor lets you choose Quick add (essentials only, fastest) or Guided setup. For a strategic or approved (AVL) supplier where you want classification, address, terms, and supplied parts captured up front, choose Guided setup — it opens the 5-step wizard (Identity, Address, Terms, Supply Items, Review). There is no convert-from-lead path for vendors."},{"id":"vc2","text":"In the Guided vendor wizard, which step actually creates the vendor record, and is therefore required?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Address"},{"id":"b","text":"Terms"},{"id":"c","text":"Identity (company name + contact)","isCorrect":true},{"id":"d","text":"Supply Items"}],"explanation":"The Identity step (company name, contact name, email, phone) creates the vendor record, so company name is required there. Until Identity is completed, nothing is saved. Address, Terms, and Supply Items are optional; Review is the required final confirmation."},{"id":"vc3","text":"On a vendor's Catalog tab, what does the Approved (green check) flag on a supplied part represent?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The catalog entry has been synced from QuickBooks"},{"id":"b","text":"The vendor is cleared to supply this part — the Approved Vendor List (AVL) marker","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The part has at least one price tier defined"},{"id":"d","text":"The purchase order for this part has been approved"}],"explanation":"The Approved toggle is the Approved Vendor List (AVL) marker: this vendor is qualified/cleared to supply this part. Approved rows show a green check; un-approved rows show a blocked icon. Purchasing uses it to steer buyers toward qualified sources. It is unrelated to accounting sync, pricing, or PO approval."},{"id":"vc4","text":"You star Vendor A as the preferred source for Part X. Vendor B was your preferred source for Part X before. What happens?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Both Vendor A and Vendor B are now preferred for Part X"},{"id":"b","text":"Vendor B's star clears on its own — a part can have only one preferred source at a time","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The system blocks the change until you manually un-star Vendor B"},{"id":"d","text":"Part X drops off Vendor B's catalog entirely"}],"explanation":"A part can have only one preferred source at a time. Star Vendor A and the star clears on whoever held it before (Vendor B), so \"who do we normally buy this from?\" always has one clean answer. Vendor B still lists the part in its catalog and stays a valid source — only the preferred star moved."},{"id":"vc5","text":"A part in a vendor's catalog has price tiers of $2.00 at min qty 1, $1.60 at min qty 100, and $1.35 at min qty 500. What unit price applies to an order of 250 units?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"$2.00 — the base tier always applies"},{"id":"b","text":"$1.60 — the qty-100 tier wins because 100 ≤ 250 < 500","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"$1.35 — the lowest available price always applies"},{"id":"d","text":"An average of the three tiers"}],"explanation":"Price resolution picks the tier with the highest Min Quantity that is still ≤ the requested quantity. For 250 units, the qty-100 tier ($1.60) wins because 100 ≤ 250 but the qty-500 tier isn't reached. Order 1,000 and the qty-500 tier ($1.35) would win."},{"id":"vc6","text":"You need to onboard a distributor's full catalog of parts they supply, with vendor part numbers and lead times. What's the most efficient way?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Add each part one at a time with the + Add button"},{"id":"b","text":"Use the Import button on the Catalog tab: download the template, fill the CSV, then review the Add/Update/Error preview and Apply","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Enter all the parts during the Supply Items step of the guided wizard"},{"id":"d","text":"Create a purchase order — receiving will add the parts to the vendor's catalog automatically"}],"explanation":"The Catalog tab's Import button handles bulk onboarding. Download the template for the exact columns, fill the CSV, and the two-state dialog shows a preview tagging each row Add, Update, or Error with a summary. Apply stays disabled until errors are fixed. Import matches on part number, so existing entries update rather than duplicate. The Supply Items wizard step is just a pointer to do this on the Catalog tab afterward."},{"id":"vc7","text":"Why do you add a new price tier (with effective dates) instead of editing the old price in place, and where do you review what you used to pay?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"You don't — editing a tier just overwrites the price and keeps no record"},{"id":"b","text":"To keep the price history; you review it with the history (clock) action, which opens the Price Tier History","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Because tiers can't be changed once a PO is placed"},{"id":"d","text":"Past pricing lives only in QuickBooks after a sync"}],"explanation":"Adding a new tier (often with a future start date) instead of painting over the old one keeps the record of what you actually paid. The history (clock) action on a catalog row opens the Price Tier History — the running log of prices added and retired. That kept history is what lets the scorecard measure how much a vendor's prices have crept."}]}"""
