        // ── Advanced Reference (Reference) ───────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Vendors — Advanced Reference",
            Slug = "vendors-reference",
            Summary = "Deeper how-to for an experienced buyer: off-quote price warnings and the variance you allow, the all-vendors performance comparison report, the vendor-readiness check, bulk import tips, manufacturer vs distributor, keeping one preferred source, and not losing a half-finished vendor.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Reference,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 90,
            AppRoutes = """["/vendors"]""",
            Tags = """["vendors","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## When a PO price doesn't match the quote\n\nPut a price on a PO line that's well off the vendor's quoted break, and the system flags the line so you can catch a fat-fingered number or a stale quote before it goes out. You decide how far off is \"off\" by setting the allowed variance — the wiggle room in percent:\n\n1. **On the vendor** — set an allowed variance for a specific supplier when that relationship runs looser or tighter. This one wins for that vendor.\n2. **Shop-wide** — a default variance that covers every vendor without its own.\n3. **A default of 5%** — used when you haven't set either.\n\nEach line's price is checked against the quoted break for that quantity, and it's flagged when the gap is bigger than the variance you allow. Two cases worth knowing: if there's no quoted price for that break yet, the line is flagged so you get a nudge to record the first price while you're there; and the bigger the gap, the louder the warning — a swing past about a quarter over quote is treated as high-risk and worth a second look before you commit. Treat the flag as a checkpoint, not a block: you can still place the order once you've confirmed the price is right.\n\n## Comparing all your vendors at once\n\nThe scorecard on a vendor grades one supplier. The **performance comparison report** lines up all your **active** vendors side by side for a date range — one row each showing on-time percent, quality percent, total spend, overall score, grade, and a trend arrow, best score at the top. It defaults to the last 12 months. The **trend** arrow compares this period against the one before it of the same length, so you can see who's improving and who's slipping (no arrow means there's no earlier period to compare against yet). This is your go-to for a sourcing review or a QBR when you're deciding where to consolidate spend or who to put on a corrective-action plan.\n\n## Is this vendor ready to buy from?\n\nThe top of a vendor's details shows a small readiness check — a quick read on whether the record has everything your shop's setup needs before you lean on this supplier:\n\n- **Green \"Ready\"** — nothing's missing for how your shop is set up.\n- **Amber \"Incomplete for…\"** — something a part of your workflow wants isn't filled in yet; click it to see exactly what, such as a Tax ID or payment terms.\n\nIt's guidance, not a gate — a vendor can be perfectly usable and still show amber if, say, you've turned on features that expect a Tax ID this supplier hasn't given you. Treat it as a to-do list for tidying up a new supplier, not a wall stopping you from ordering.\n\n## Bulk import — the columns and the errors\n\nWhen you load a supplier's catalog from a spreadsheet, the **Download template** link gives you the exact columns: part number, the vendor's part number, manufacturer name, the vendor's manufacturer part number, lead time in days, minimum order quantity, pack size, country of origin, HTS code, and notes. Then:\n\n1. **Pick a file** — drag in or browse for the spreadsheet.\n2. **Review the preview** — every row comes back tagged **Add**, **Update**, or **Error**, with a running count. It matches on part number against what the vendor already lists, so a part they already have updates in place instead of doubling up, and a new one is added.\n\nRows with a problem are tagged **Error** with a reason, and **Apply** stays grayed out until every one is fixed — clean up the spreadsheet and re-import. When it's all green, Apply saves the adds and updates in one go. The usual culprits are a part number that doesn't exist in your parts list yet, or a blank required column.\n\n## Manufacturer or distributor?\n\nThe **Is Manufacturer** switch on the catalog form records what the vendor's role is for that part — and it's worth getting right, because it changes what you quote back to them and how you trace the part:\n\n- **On** — the vendor makes the part. They're the manufacturer, so there's one part number to record.\n- **Off (distributor)** — the vendor resells someone else's part. Record both the vendor's own number and the original manufacturer's part number (MPN). That MPN can differ from your drawing's part number, and having it means you can re-source the same part from a second distributor without guessing.\n\n## Keeping one preferred source per part\n\nA part can have only **one preferred source at a time**. Star a vendor as preferred and the star clears on every other supplier of that part, so \"who do we normally buy this from?\" always has one clean answer — and the change is stamped in the activity history so anyone can see when the go-to source moved and who moved it.\n\nReordering and any auto-generated POs use the preferred vendor's lead time, minimum order quantity, and pack size, so keep the star on the supplier you actually want the system defaulting to. In the catalog, the preferred row shows a filled star you toggle right from the list. When a part has just one source, it shows as a single card instead of a table.\n\n## Not losing a half-finished vendor\n\nThe vendor form holds onto your work as you go. If you get interrupted — you close the tab or step away and get signed out — your unsaved entries are kept and offered back the next time you're in, both right after you sign in and as a banner on the form. The kept draft only clears when you discard it on purpose, save the vendor, or leave it untouched for long enough. The guided setup wizard works a little differently: it saves each step as you finish it, so you can close it and reopen right where you left off — handy when onboarding a strategic supplier turns into a two-day back-and-forth for their certs and terms.","sections":[]}"""
